There is growing consensus in Europe that an active set of approaches to welfare known as Social Investment will improve human capital, enable more people to participate in society, and reduce intergenerational deprivation, yet implementation has been uneven across member states and much remains to be learned, especially with regard to regional and local realities of Social Investment. This proposal is for EURO-3-2014: European societies after the crisis. Within that call its focus is on ‘Innovative social investment approaches for the modernisation of social policies and services’. We will deploy multidisciplinary research on innovative ways of implementing and financing social welfare that promise lasting benefits.  Our aims are threefold:  
-Identify and evaluate existing innovative and strategic approaches to social welfare reform at a regional and local level;
-Explore social and psychological impact of these innovations on individuals and communities;
-Collate useful, practical learning from this new body of evidence and mobilise it to inform policy and practice across the EU. 
We will deliver on our first two aims through:
• Macro and micro-level research on social investment policies and initiatives;
• Mixed method case studies in ten member states,  taking account of local and regional  networks,  institutions and assets,  as well as national and European policies;
• A distinct understanding of Social Investment utilizing ‘social innovation’ as a key concept; 
• A strong user voice, ensured throughout the project by recruiting  and training  ‘Community Reporters’. 

Approximately a third of the resource on this project is devoted to impact generation (Aim 3). Results from the research  will be assimilated in a Foresight Analysis where we will work with policy makers, user-led organizations and social entrepreneurs to consider options for innovative ways of implementing and financing social welfare systems in the future. 10 impact partners will assist us.

Hydrogen in Schools (HySchools) seeks to provide a step change in education on the topic of Hydrogen Fuel Cells Technology (HFCT) across Europe, driven by the university partners & supported by all partners to ensure its maximum impact on education and industry. HySchools is a partnership of 4 Universities with specialisms in HFCTs, 1 Regional Authority, 1 Energy Agency, 1 Science Park and 1 training provider based in 6 countries across Europe, which together will work to create teaching resources for the HFCT sector that educates learners and teachers alike, at all levels of the educational system. 

Hydrogen fuel cells and the ‘hydrogen economy’ are considered a big solution to our future clean energy needs. However, the skills required to support the growing industry are lacking and in order to remove some of the barriers that exist (lack of teaching resources, confidence of teachers to teach, lack of awareness of wider uses for HFCTs and links to wider curriculum etc), a programme of practical educational resources for university students, pupils, teacher training departments and school teachers is required. 

This is happening at a time when the trajectory for employment in the sector is upwards. The Fuel Cells and Hydrogen Joint Undertaking (FCHJU) suggests the number of jobs has been increasing in the sector by approximately 6% per year since 2007 to 4,000 (FTE) today globally and Survey respondents in the industry expect employment growth of 9% pa, doubling the number of jobs 2013-20 to around 8,000 globally. A Call for proposals from the Commission funded FCH Joint Undertaking (FCH-04-3-2017) sets out need ' a firm basis needs to be prepared for an EU-wide human resources development of scientists & especially engineers to feed the growing European fuel cell and hydrogen (FCH) industry. The SET Plan Education, established in 2012/2013, expected a human resource of 57,000 highly skilled staff required by 2020, and 190,000 by 2030 in the FCH business. Supplying this resource is a major challenge in reliably building the FCH value and supply chain.' The achievement of higher level skills in HFCTs is hindered by a lack of teaching in schools. 

The needs of the education system are equally matched with a demand for this step change in provision from industry to enable it to draw on an a highly skilled, prepared and enthusiastic future workforce. However the two require effort to facilitate the required educational solution and resource at all levels. 

Needs in relation to the education systems we seek to influence include:

- in Secondary and Higher level schools the subject of HFCT applications is only taught from a scientific perspective, not linked or across wider disciplines and at primary school it is not taught at all;
- teachers do not understand how to teach about HFCTs;
- teachers, especially at primary schools require additional CPD opportunities to help them deliver;
- practical teaching resources are needed for all age levels to aid both learning and teaching;
- even Chemistry teachers, whilst they are aware of HFCTs,  do not have expertise in teaching about HFCTs or their industry application;
- there are no current direct links between most schools and the industry;
- a lack of activity in all of the above means there are no role models or aspirational stories to engage and energise young people;
- as a result there is a lack of available equipment to teach appropriately and in a practical way;
- in order to influence curriculum change it requires an understanding and appropriate input with cyclical reviews of the curriculum and ongoing dialogue with exam boards.

To overcome these barriers HySchools will focus its activity on the provision of 7 Intellectual Outputs covering: 

1) Education & Industry Alignment of need and demand 
2) Creation of practical resource for secondary schools
3) Creation of practical resource for Post 16
4) Online HFCT resource for schools & industry 
5) Demonstration & Awareness Open Days
6) Toolkit for integration within EHTN  linked to higher level skills
7) Dissemination

 HySchools aims to bring teaching of HFCTs across a range of age levels and subject matters and as a resut it will immediately impact on Pupils, Teacher Trainers, Trainee Teachers, Teachers, Careers Advisors, Industry, Stakeholders & Policy Makers and ultimately in the future university students across a range of disciplines to provide the industry with the higher level skills it requires.
